{"cursor":"7624","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":" in groups of gravity waves on the surface of deep water. The red dot moves with\n the phase velocity, and the green dots propagate with the group velocity. In\n this deep-water case, the phase velocity is twice the group velocity. The red\n dot overtakes two green dots when moving from the left to the right of the\n figure. New waves seem to emerge at the back of a wave group, grow in\n amplitude until they are at the center of the group, and vanish at the wave\n group front. For surface gravity waves, the water particle velocities are\n much smaller than the phase velocity, in most cases.]]\n\n\n\nThe 'phase velocity' of a wave is the rate at which the phase of the wave\npropagates in space. This is the velocity at which the phase of any one\nfrequency component of the wave travels. For such a component, any given phase\nof the wave (for example, the crest) will appear to travel at the phase\nvelocity. The phase velocity is given in terms of the wavelength Î» (lambda) and\nperiod T as\n\n: v_\\mathrm{p} = \\frac{\\lambda}{T}.\n\nOr, equivalently, in terms of the wave's angular frequency Ï, which specifies\nthe number of oscillations per unit of time, and wavenumber k, which specifies\nthe number of oscillations per unit of space, by\n\n: v_\\mathrm{p} = \\frac{\\omega}{k}.\n\nTo understand where this equation comes from, imagine a basic sine wave,\nA cos (kxâÏt). Given time t, the source produces Ït oscillations. At\nthe same time, the initial wave front propagates away from the source through\nthe space to the distance x to fit the same amount of oscillations,\nkx = Ït. So that the propagation velocity v is\nv = x/t = Ï/k. The wave propagates faster when higher\nfrequency oscillations are distributed less densely in space. Formally, Î¦ = kxâÏt is the phase. Since\nÏ = âdÎ¦/dt and k = +dÎ¦/dx, the wave velocity is\nv = dx/dt = Ï/k.\n","linknr":188,"url":"Phase_velocity","recorded":13